    <title>Preview Dot Surfaces Rendering</title>
    
    <section title="New Surface Rendering options">

<table border="1">
<tr>
<td>
<h2>ddt</h2>
<appletExample>
<![CDATA[
<applet name="jmol" code="JmolApplet" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
        width="300" height="300" mayscript="true" >
	<param name="emulate"   value="chime" />
        <param name="load"      value="ddt.xyz.gz" />
</applet>]]>
</appletExample>
</td>

<td>
Jmol has the ability to show two types of 'dots' surfaces. The first is a
vanderWalls dots surface, where the dots are shown at the vanderWaals
radius for all atoms.<br />
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="dots on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="dots on" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="dots off" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="dots off" />
</applet><br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="cpk 25%" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="cpk 25%" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="cpk 50%" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="cpk 50%" />
</applet><br />


<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="cpk 95%" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="cpk 95%" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="cpk off" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="cpk off" />
</applet><br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="wireframe on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="wireframe on" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="wireframe 0.1" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="wireframe 0.1" />
</applet><br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="wireframe 0.3" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="wireframe 0.3" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="wireframe off" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="wireframe off" />
</applet><br />




The second type of dots surface you can display is a Connolly or
Solvent Accessible Surface. The model is that this is the surface which is
accessible by a probe sphere. This command interacts with the 'dots'
command.<br />
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="dots off; set solvent on; dots on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="dots off; set solvent on; dots on" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="dots off; set solvent off; dots on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="dots off; set solvent off; dots on" />
</applet><br />

The default probe size is 1.2 Angstrom, a probe size used for water.
So these first two buttons do the same thing. But you need to use
these in combination with the 'dots' buttons above. <br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="set solvent on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="set solvent on" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="set solvent 1.2" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="set solvent 1.2" />
</applet><br />
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="set solvent 2.0" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="set solvent 2.0" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="set solvent off" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="set solvent off" />
</applet><br />

By default, convex dots on the outside of the atom spheres
inherit the color of the atom. Saddle dots are shown in blue.
There are explicit color commands for controlling dot color. <br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="color dots yellow" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="color dots yellow" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="color dotsConvex cyan" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="color dotsConvex cyan" />
</applet><br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="color dotsSaddle hotpink" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="color dotsSaddle hotpink" />
</applet>
<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="200" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"  value="color dots none" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script" value="color dots none" />
</applet><br />

(Concave surfaces formed where three atoms come together are a problem
for me. If you are interested in this topic, please get in touch.
<b>mth@mth.com</b>) <br />

This button makes them pretty easy to see. They are the little spherical
triangles that do not have any dots. <br />

<applet code="JmolAppletControl" archive="head/JmolApplet.jar"
  height="20" width="400" mayscript="true" >
  <param name="type"  value="button" />
  <param name="label"
         value="cpk 95%; color dots yellow; set solvent on; dots on" />
  <param name="target" value="jmol" />
  <param name="script"
         value="cpk 95%; color dots yellow; set solvent on; dots on" />
</applet><br />
